            <div>
               
	<pb facs="liv_001297_0001" n="0001"/><!-- Change both @facs and @n -->
	<!-- Start each page with a <pb> formatted as above -->

<!-- If this is a letter or similar with an opener (with content such as dateline and/or salute) add it. For example: -->
<opener>
<lb rend="right"/><dateline><add place="margintop" rend="left vertical gray small" hand="#U"><!-- diagonal -->C/4/49</add> <placeName>Steamer Pearl</placeName> <add place="margintop" rend="right gray small" hand="#U">MS 7/1</add><!-- I am not sure how to encode "Steamer Pearl". Please advise. JM --><!-- It's a ship, so I guess placeName is OK. AW -->
<lb/><date when="1858-03-25">25 March 1858</date>
</dateline>
<add place="marginleft"><hi rend="underline">Private</hi></add>
<lb/><salute>My Dear Sir</salute>
</opener>
<lb/><p><space extent="6" unit="chars"/>We have been going   
<lb/>at the rate of <measure>200 miles</measure> 
<lb/>a day ever since we
<lb/>left <placeName><settlement type="city">Liverpool</settlement></placeName> on the
<lb/><date when="1858-03-10">10<hi rend="underline">th</hi></date> and are now in
<lb/>glorious summer weather
<lb/>pitying the natives we
<lb/>have left behind in
<lb/>their miserable frost
<lb/>and now - We go
<lb/>into <placeName><country>Sierra Leone</country></placeName>
<lb/>today and will get
<lb/>nicely thawed out
    
    <pb facs="liv_001297_0002" n="0002"/>
<lb/>after all the chills we
<lb/>endured in <placeName><country>England</country></placeName>
<lb/>The Pearl has done
<lb/>her duty nicely and
<lb/>the captain, a good
<lb/>man, is thoroughly
<lb/>up to his duty - 
<lb/>My companions
<lb/>seem all men of
<lb/>of the right stamp and
<lb/>I am thankful
<lb/>to a kind Providence
<lb/>for favouring us
<lb/>thus far. When we
<lb/>have <unclear cert="high">waled</unclear> we
<lb/>proceed to the <placeName><region>Cape</region></placeName>.</p>
<lb/><p><space extent="4" unit="chars"/>I enclose to
<lb/>you a packet of

    <pb facs="liv_001297_0003" n="0003"/>
<lb/>letters which you will
<lb/>be kind enough to
<lb/>forward to their destinations
<lb/>Any expense you
<lb/>may incur will be
<lb/>paid by <persName>M<hi rend="sup underline">r</hi> <unclear cert="low">Coults &amp;c</unclear></persName>
<lb/>We are not late enough
<lb/>to send home a certificate
<lb/>of life for this
<lb/>quarter but we shall
<lb/>do it at the <placeName><region>Cape</region></placeName>
<lb/>Will you be kind
<lb/>enough to let <persName>M<hi rend="sup underline">r</hi> Elliott</persName>
<lb/>know that <persName>M<hi rend="sup underline">r</hi> Duncan</persName>
<lb/>has furnished us with
<lb/>a most excellent
<lb/>captain - very few
<lb/>equal him in knowledge
<lb/>of his work. He formerly
<lb/>commanded one of the
<lb/>large <placeName><settlement type="city">New York</settlement></placeName> steamers</p>
    
    <pb facs="liv_001297_0004" n="0004"/>
<lb/><p>We hope to be at the    
<lb/><placeName><geogName type="river">Zambesi</geogName></placeName> by the <date when="1858-05-01">first
<lb/>of May</date>. The Colonial
<lb/>Office have acted from
<lb/>first to last in the
<lb/>most handsome way
<lb/>to us and I am sure
<lb/>I feel grateful</p>
<lb/><p><space extent="4" unit="chars"/>I am so sorry that
<lb/>we did not arrange the
<lb/>insurance so that we
<lb/>could have gone in to
<lb/><placeName><settlement type="town">Loanda</settlement></placeName>. I would have
<lb/>sent a specimen of the
<lb/><placeName><country>Angola</country></placeName> <term type="foodstuff">coffee</term> which
<lb/>would have pleased you
<lb/>more than <term type="insect">beetles</term> <term type="insect">bugs</term> 
<lb/>&amp; <term type="insect">cockroaches</term>, it is the
<lb/>finest I ever tasted and
<lb/>I wish it were known
<lb/>at home.</p> <closer>Accept of my 
<lb/>hearty thanks for all
<lb/>your kindness <salute>I am &amp;C</salute> <signed><persName>David Livingstone</persName></signed></closer>

